        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use a uniform spectral resolution of 0.976 MHz across 4 SPWs of 1.8 GHz bandwidth each. The key lines to cover in the setup are H30a, CH3CN 12-11 and several CH3OH lines (see Fig. 2 of the proposal). The spectral resolution of 1.3km/s is sufficient to resolve the accretion flows in the molecular gas and ionized gas. The 230 GHz continuum will be constructed from line free channels.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested angular resolution of 0.12" (1/2 of the gravitational radius of 0".25) is sufficient to spatially resolve the accretion flow in the ionized gas, but is also sensitive to the high density molecular gas surrounding the HII region at a scale of 2". The more extended emission (~&gt; 2") of molecular lines and the 230 GHz continuum is available through existing SMA observations, that are sensitive enough to the angular scale of 0.63-22" (i.e. 6-393 kilo lambda), and will serve as the short-spacing database to further improve the spatial dynamic range. The compact continuum source of our target will enable self-calibrations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We used the VLA 1.3 cm continuum image (0".1 resolution) from Sollins et al. 2005, the SMA 1.3mm continuum and H30a data (0.9" resolution) from Keto et al. 2008 to estimate the H30a line flux for the ALMA observations. The free-free continuum flux is expected to be 100 mJy/0.1" beam at 230 GHz. The recombination line to continuum ratio is 1.2:1 according to SMA data and theoretical expectations for the hydrogen recomb lines. Thus we find an H30a line flux of 120 mJy/0.1" beam.  With the total observing time, we can achieve an S/N ratio of &gt; 100 at the H30a line peak. The CH3CN and CH3OH lines at the scale of &lt;1000 AU are expected to be &gt;100 K in brightness temperature. With the 1sigma rms of 1.9K per channel, we can reach an S/N of &gt;50 at the line peaks which are expectd to be optically thick.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>G10.6 is known to be line rich in Band 6 according to our exiting SMA observations in a similar frequency setup. We request the visibility data be saved in its full spectral resolution with no averaging, so that this ALMA dataset can be explored to its full potential for kinematics, physics and chemistry.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
